I want to build a status monitoring web app that tracks the health of my other applications. This app will have three different interfaces:
- a CLI with which you can interact directly with the instance when logged in the same server
- an API with which you can interact remotely (eg through curl)
- a user friendly React app

We will implement this using TypeScript.

These three interfaces will share code. To begin with, we will have one domain entity:
    interface AppStatus {
        id: AppStatusID;
        name: string;
        ok: boolean;
        checkedAt: Date;
    }

We need the following modular structure:
    - src/domain       -> contains domain models (AppStatus interface)
    - src/core         -> shared business logic
    - src/cli          -> CLI specific code
    - src/web-api      -> REST API server code
    - src/web-ui       -> React SPA code
    - src/bootstrap    -> initialization code (will be used later for database connection)
    - src/persistent-memory -> database layer implementation (only migrations for now, will use Drizzle ORM later)

## React Web UI

The React app will be very simple. For the moment it should have one route:
 - /  -> the home of the app; will fetch and display all app statuses via GET /api/app-statuses

Note that this is an SPA, so we need react-router-dom for routing.

The home page should:
- Make a GET request to /api/app-statuses on mount
- Display a list of all app statuses showing: name, ok status (boolean), and checkedAt timestamp
- Use Bootstrap for basic styling (include from CDN in index.html)

## Web API

The WEB-API will have one single endpoint:
- GET /api/app-statuses -> returns all app statuses (hardcoded data for now)

The API should:
- Use Express
- Serve the React build as static files in production
- Handle 404 responses appropriately
- Use the bootstrap module to initialize dependencies (even though we're using hardcoded data for now)
- Include a catch-all route for client-side routing

## CLI

The CLI will be called like this:
    `status get app-statuses`
    `status run-migrations`

The CLI should:
- Accept commands via process.argv
- Use the bootstrap module to initialize dependencies
